5. std::flat_map for extension stats
compute_extension_stats builds an unordered_map then sorts at the end. Since you always end up with a sorted output, std::flat_map (C++23) — which is a sorted, contiguous key-value structure — fits better and has better cache behaviour.


std::flat_map	analyzer extension stats	Low-medium — cache win, fits the usage





unning actions in parallel — yes, this is real
Looking at main.cpp:43-46:


for (const auto& action : result.actions)
    std::visit(executor, action);
Actions run sequentially. But compute_extension_stats, compute_recent_files, and compute_largest_N_Files are completely independent — they only read tree. If a user runs --extensions --recent 7d --largest-files 10, that's three full O(N) passes over all files done one after another.

These could be launched with std::async in parallel, results collected into a vector in submission order, then printed sequentially. The Executor's cached state (file_stats, metrics, empty_dirs) would need to be pre-warmed before spawning, since those use mutable optional which isn't thread-safe. But the heavy compute functions themselves only take const DirectoryTree& — safe to run concurrently.

That's the most interesting remaining optimization and it's cross-platform.

